						<div id="content" class="8u skel-cell-important">
							<section>
								<header>
									<h2>Music Maestro</h2>
									<span class="byline">Fall 2015-Spring 2016 [Written on 10-8-2016]</span>
								</header>
								<p><a href="#" class="image full"><img src="../../images/MusicMaestro.jpg" alt=""></a></p>
								<p>The freshman engineering program at Pitt normally teaches basic computer skills (Microsoft office, java script, HTML) first semester and basic programming skills (Matlab, C++) in the second semester. There is an option for more tech savvy students to take an honors equivalent which skips the basic computer skills and teaches programming to first semester freshman engineering students. This opens up the second semester for one of two options: a research for credit course, or a course on prototyping and design thinking.</p>

								<p>ENGR0716, more commonly known as the Art of Making, is the latter of the two, and was an experimental class that was under actively under development throughout 2014 and 2015. By sheer luck, I ended up having the opportunity to take it the very first year it was offered. I can't even begin to describe the wide variety of topics covered in this class, even after TAing for it this past spring. To sum it up briefly, we learned about how to think around problems, and how to develop basic prototypes for potential solutions using a variety of techniques and materials from foam-core to microcontrollers.</p>
							
								<p>With approximately four weeks left in the course, we organized into groups for a capstone project, which would serve as a substitute for a final. This was a culmination of the skills we'd learned in the past 12 weeks, and a reflection of our personal interests. As a cellist, I realized that the transcription aspect of musical composition was unintuitive and unnecessarily difficult for the average string player. I proposed this as a potential project idea and piqued the interest of four other musically minded students in our class. Together, we devised a MIDI (musical instrument digital interface) equivalent</p>
							</section>
						</div>

